# In-app documentation pages

Every application I build must include three pieces of user-facing documentation,
built into the app itself (e.g. as navigation pages/tabs), so they can be shown
or hidden later as needed, plus a keyboard-shortcuts reference (see #4). If the app
has no GUI, provide the docs as `docs/` markdown files instead.

## 1. Getting Started
A short, task-focused quick start: what the app is in one line, then the few
steps a new user needs (how to open it, do the core action, and the key
shortcuts). Keep it simple and scannable.

## 2. Roadmap & Maintenance
Two parts:
- **Roadmap** — what's shipped now, what's next, and what's planned later.
- **Maintenance** — practical notes for keeping it running over time: how to
  update the runtime/dependencies, what to do when the environment or hardware
  changes, where logs/diagnostics live, key internals to look at, and known
  limitations.

## 3. Source & Builder (About)
A page that helps me find and improve the app later (I rely on this for memory):
- **Builder** (e.g. "Cursor") and the AI assistant/tools used.
- **Repository** — the source-control/GitHub repository URL, shown right after the
  builder, with a button to open it in the browser. Auto-detect it from the local git
  remote ("origin") when the source is present, with a baked-in fallback; never rely on
  a hand-typed value that can go stale.
- **Source files location** — the project/repo path, baked in at build time, with a
  button to open the folder (and to open it in the builder/editor).
- **Currently running from** — the live executable location.
- Persist this to disk and **auto-update it when the app is launched from a new
  location** (in case the files are moved), showing a note when the path changed.

## 4. Keyboard shortcuts reference (always visible)
Expose every keyboard shortcut/hotkey in the UI so I never have to remember them:
- Put it in an **always-visible spot** (e.g. a small card in the sidebar/footer that
  shows on every screen), not buried on a page. A dedicated page is fine *in addition*,
  but the quick reference must be glanceable without navigating.
- List each action with its key(s) shown as key "caps" (e.g. `Esc`, `F5`, `Ctrl + Alt + D`).
- Show the **live** shortcut, not a hard-coded string: if a global hotkey can fall back
  to an alternative when its preferred combo is taken, bind the label to the one that
  actually registered so it's never wrong.
- Keep it in sync as shortcuts are added/changed; also mention them in Getting Started.

## Rules
- Prefer real in-app pages (navigation entries) over external files for GUI apps.
- Make them easy to hide/remove without breaking the app.
- Keep pages updated as features ship — move items from "next" to "shipped".
